aken by Saudi actors and institutions to exert religious influence far beyond the kingdom's borders. Michael Farquhar draws on Arabic sources, including biographical materials, memoirs, syllabi, and back issues of the Islamic University journal, as well as interviews with former staff and students, to explore the institution's history and faculty, the content and style of instruction, and the trajectories and experiences of its students. Countering typical assumptions, Farquhar argues that the project undertaken through the Islamic University amounts to something more complex than just the one-way "export" of Wahhabism. Through transnational networks of students and faculty, this Saudi state-funded religious mission also relies upon, and has in turn been influenced by, far-reaching circulations of persons and ideas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aIslam and statexSaudi Arabia. 0aIslam and statezSaudi Arabia. 0aIslamic fundamentalism. 0aIslamic religious educationxSaudi Arabia. 0aIslamic religious educationzSaudi Arabia. 0aTransnationalismxSaudi Arabia. 0aTransnationalism. 0aWahhābīyahzSaudi ArabiaxInfluence. 0aWahhābīyahxInfluencexSaudi Arabia. 4aIslamic education. 4aSalafism. 4aSaudi Arabia. 4aWahhabism. 4amigration. 4areligious economies. 4aspiritual capital. 4atransnational history. 4atransnational religion. 4atransnationalism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Islamic Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503600270zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503600270423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503600270.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles